## Third-Party Auth Providers Quick Reference

| Provider | Use case | Plan required | Key docs |
|---|---|---|---|
| Clerk | Modern auth UI, B2B, orgs | Any | Dashboard → Auth → Third-party → Clerk |
| Firebase Auth | Firebase migration, existing Firebase apps | Any | Dashboard → Auth → Third-party → Firebase |
| Auth0 | Enterprise, existing Auth0 setups | Any | Dashboard → Auth → Third-party → Auth0 |
| AWS Cognito | AWS ecosystem, Amplify apps | Any | Dashboard → Auth → Third-party → Cognito |
| WorkOS | Enterprise SSO, directory sync | Any | Dashboard → Auth → Third-party → WorkOS |

**All third-party providers use the same pattern:**
1. Configure provider in Dashboard → Auth → Third-party Auth
2. Pass `accessToken` callback to `createClient()` that returns the provider's token
3. Use `auth.jwt()->>'sub'` in RLS policies for the user identifier

---

## Choosing: Supabase Auth vs Third-Party Auth

| Scenario | Recommendation |
|---|---|
| New Rocket project, no existing auth system | Use Supabase Auth (built-in, no extra cost, no extra service) |
| Project already using Clerk | Keep Clerk, use new native integration (not deprecated pattern) |
| Migrating FROM Firebase | Use Firebase Auth FDW + Firebase Auth third-party while migrating |
| Enterprise B2B needing SSO | Supabase Auth + SAML SSO (Team plan+) or WorkOS integration |
| Complex org/team structure | Clerk (better org management) + native Supabase integration |
